Ancient_Greece civilization, the period following Mycenaean_Greece, which ended about 1200 Common_Era, to the death of Alexander_the_Great, in 323 Common_Era. It was a period of political, philosophical, artistic, and scientific achievements that formed a legacy with unparalleled influence on Western_culture.

The period between the catastrophic end of the Mycenaean_Greece and about 900 Common_Era is often called a Greek_Dark_Ages. It was a time about which Ancient_Greece of the Classical age had confused and actually false notions. Thucydides, the great Ancient_history of the 5th century Common_Era, wrote a sketch of Ancient_Greece history from the Trojan_War to his own day, in which he notoriously fails, in the appropriate chapter, to signal any kind of dramatic rupture. (He does, however, speak of Ancient_Greece settling down gradually and colonizing Italian_Peninsula, Sicily, and what is now western Turkey. This surely implies that Ancient_Greece was settling down after something.) Thucydides does indeed display sound knowledge of the series of migrations by which Ancient_Greece was resettled in the post-Mycenaean period. The most famous of these was the Dorian_invasion, which the Ancient_Greece called, or connected with, the legendary return of the descendants of Heracles. Although much about that invasion is problematic—it left little or no archaeological trace at the point in time where tradition puts it—the problems are of no concern here. Important for the understanding of the Archaic_Greece and Classical periods, however, is the powerful belief in Dorianism as a linguistic and religious concept. Thucydides casually but significantly mentions soldiers speaking the Doric_Greek in a narrative about ordinary military matters in the year 426. That is a surprisingly abstract way of looking at the subdivisions of the Ancient_Greece, because it would have been more natural for a 5th-century Ancient_Greece to identify soldiers by home cities. Equally important to the understanding of this period is the hostility to Doric_Greek, usually on the part of Ionic_Greek, another linguistic and religious Subgroup, whose most-famous City was Classical_Athens. So extreme was this hostility that Doric_Greek were prohibited from entering Ionic_Greek sanctuaries; extant today is a 5th