Phenomena such as the tension between Doric_Greek and Ionic_Greek that have their origins in the Greek_Dark_Ages are a reminder that Ancient_Greece civilization did not emerge either unannounced or uncontaminated by what had gone before. The_Dark_Age_(Buffy_the_Vampire_Slayer) itself is beyond the scope of this article. One is bound to notice, however, that archaeological finds tend to call into question the whole concept of a Greek_Dark_Ages by showing that certain features of Ancient_Greece civilization once thought not to antedate about 800 Common_Era can actually be pushed back by as much as two centuries. One example, chosen for its relevance to the emergence of the Ancient_Greece Polis, or polis, will suffice. In 1981 archaeology pulled back the curtain on the darkest phase of all, the Protogeometric_style (c. 1075–900 Common_Era), which takes its name from the geometric shapes painted on Pottery. A grave, rich by the standards of any period, was uncovered at a site called Lefkandi on Euboea, the island along the eastern flank of Attica (the territory controlled by Athens). The_Grave_(poem), which dates to about 1000 Common_Era, contains the (probably cremated) remains of a man and a woman. The large bronze vessel in which the man’s ashes were deposited came from Cyprus, and the gold items buried with the woman are splendid and sophisticated in their workmanship. Remains of horses were found as well; the animals had been buried with their Snaffle_bit bits. The_Grave_(poem) was within a large collapsed house, whose form anticipates that of the Greek_language temples two centuries later. Previously it had been thought that those temples were one of the first manifestations of the monumentalizing associated with the beginnings of the Polis. Thus, that find and those made in a set of nearby cemeteries in the years before 1980 attesting further contacts between Ancient_Egypt and Cyprus between 1000 and 800 Common_Era are important evidence. They show that one corne